g.text: Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report
MMWR
February 7, 2020
Vol. 69
No. 5
US Department of Health and Human Services/Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
2019-nCoV symptoms are similar to those of influenza
(e.g., fever, cough, or sore throat), and the outbreak is occur-
ring during a time of year when respiratory illnesses from
influenza, respiratory syncytial virus, and other respiratory
viruses are highly prevalent. To prevent influenza, all persons
aged â‰¥6 months should receive an annual influenza vaccine,
and vaccination is still available and effective in helping to
prevent influenza (
). Reducing the number of persons in
the United States with seasonal influenza will reduce possible
confusion with 2019-nCoV infection and possible additional
risk to patients with seasonal influenza. Public health authori-
ties are monitoring the situation closely. As more is learned
about this novel virus and this outbreak, CDC will rapidly
incorporate new knowledge into guidance for action.
